Darryl Miles (darryl_miles@au1.ibm.com)
2017-09-29 08:49:04

E-FOTA brings firmware management capabilities to MaaS360. This feature allows the IT to manage firmware updates installed on the Samsung devices. Previously, all the devices received firmware update as soon as they are available on the Play Store, without IT having any control over it. On top of that, the unplanned firmware updates would sometimes break the enterprise apps due to compatibility issues.

MaaS360 integrates E-FOTA to overcome the challenges associated with firmware updates. With E-FOTA, IT can pre-test the firmware update against the enterprise apps before rolling it out to the devices. This solution also ensures that all the devices in a team run a same and stable firmware version which is compatible with the enterprise apps.

See - https://goo.gl/pX2BC2

Jesus Latorre (jesocas@us.ibm.com)
2017-12-08 16:20:18

Hi @NicolasR are you planning on doing an active/passive HA? Or are you looking to do active/active? How many EAG appliances are you going to use? Load Balancer or DNS failovers are usually the better approach to take for an HA instance. If using a load balancer though, make sure you're persisting the connection of your devices though so that it doesn't jump from 1 EAG to another EAG and end up causing connection issues.

In this advanced lab, you learn how to configure Advanced Laptop and Desktop management services. You manage and distribute Windows patching and app updates for Windows 7 and Windows 10 devices using MaaS360's Unified Endpoint Management capabilities. You learn how to configure settings and review collected data to ensure your devices are secured against risk, threats, and vulnerabilities. 2018-09-18 15:12:22

Okay, so… curious as to how Identity Manager SSO/Password-less works. More specifically on Android

Woody (eric.woodland@trust.tc)
2018-09-18 15:13:58

Is it based on the MaaS360 Container?

Woody (eric.woodland@trust.tc)
2018-09-18 15:14:14

Based on what I see here, that sort of seems to be the angle they’re working: https://www.ibm.com/developerworks/community/blogs/4d57676c-a8cd-4907-9910-b21f35a1e5c6/entry/MaaS360_introduces_IBM_Cloud_Identity_integration_for_mobile_app_Single_Sign_on_SSO_and_conditional_access1?lang=en

Jesus Latorre (jesocas@us.ibm.com)
2018-09-18 15:20:51

It's based on our container, correct

Jesus Latorre (jesocas@us.ibm.com)
2018-09-18 15:21:13

so what we did is we build the entire SSO product into our app, since Android doesn't have a native SSO like iOS

Jesus Latorre (jesocas@us.ibm.com)
2018-09-18 15:21:44

so, cert comes down and installs inside MaaS360, and that authenticates to Cloud Identity and establishes the SSO session to whatever apps are being configured

Jesus Latorre (jesocas@us.ibm.com)
2018-09-18 15:21:57

of course, you'll still have to enter your email address for tenant discovery

Woody (eric.woodland@trust.tc)
2018-09-18 15:54:25

So, in order to leverage SSO for an app on Android, does it have to have any sort of SDK/Wrapper embedded as a part of the process?

Jesus Latorre (jesocas@us.ibm.com)
2018-09-18 15:55:19

no, none

Jesus Latorre (jesocas@us.ibm.com)
2018-09-18 15:55:29

There's a process to enable the app for SSO during the add app workflow

linkedin.com
Gerard Kennedy on LinkedIn: "Security controls on BYOD device with a Work Profile just got even stronger with our release of the ability to block the installation from unknown sources on the whole device, not just within the work profile. Great work from our London R&amp;D team. To implement in your EMM: set a managed configuration for “com.android.vending” with fields below to block device wide unknown sources: key: "verify_apps: device_wide_unknown_source_block" value: true Note: A user will still be able to toggle unknown sources on and off from Settings on their device, however installs from unknown sources will be blocked at install time. We are planning to improve the experience in future releases of Android."
November 22, 2018: Gerard Kennedy posted on LinkedIn

Justin Butts (justin.butts777@gmail.com)
2019-04-29 15:55:41

Can anyone explain MaaS360's "Resolved Policies" - what they are, why you'd use them? I can't find any documentation from IBM

Matthew Shaver (mshaver@us.ibm.com)
2019-04-29 16:03:03

*Thread Reply:* A resolved policy is the record of combined policies. It’s there as a way for admins to see what exactly is being applied to a device that is receiving configuration input from multiple policies by way of group assignment

Justin Butts (justin.butts777@gmail.com)
2019-04-29 16:09:12

*Thread Reply:* @Matthew Shaver Okay, that's what I was sort of imagining - so are they actual policies that you can then apply out? We have a PoC messing around with it and he's wanting to apply resolved policies to other devices

Matthew Shaver (mshaver@us.ibm.com)
2019-04-29 16:10:15

*Thread Reply:* They can not just because they’re receiving information from different sources already. It can be….. confusing, but it was only ever intended as a record for auditing

Justin Butts (justin.butts777@gmail.com)
2019-04-29 16:10:27

*Thread Reply:* Okay that is perfect, thank you!

Matthew Shaver (mshaver@us.ibm.com)

*Thread Reply:* You’re welcome!

Matthew Shaver (mshaver@us.ibm.com)
2019-05-08 22:52:02

*Thread Reply:* The crux of the issue is that precedence determines which policy a device gets when there are multiple processes assigning them. Multi-policy features just applies all assigned policies to the device - pushes every configuration and implements the strictest restrictions. I have to see what their overall workflows look like to try and get an idea of what would best suit their needs

*Thread Reply:* You can set as Corp shared device if needed: Corporate Shared: The company-owned device that is shared across multiple users. When a user signs into the MaaS360 app with the corporate or local credentials, the level of access to data, applications, and features is based on the group evaluation. When the user logs out of the MaaS360 app, MaaS360 removes the apps and policies that are distributed to the device

*Thread Reply:* There are other factors at play here as well. For instance your example of kiosk mode would be driven by a group based rule. Device groups (which this would fall under) only does a full group evaluate once every 24 hours. There are incremental evaluations for when a new user joins the group.

*Thread Reply:* If a device is enrolled to a user with Device account or device license selected then that device is linked to that user and you won’t be able to enroll any additional devices to that user without removing that device and user and making the again/removing the user from MaaS and importing again through AD

Matthew Shaver (mshaver@us.ibm.com)
2019-09-12 23:24:28

*Thread Reply:* Yeah, this is highly unusual and not a recommended practice. If you're managing multiple clients in the same portal you could even be breaking privacy laws (like GDPR or Cali compliance). There is a reason the MaaS360 cloud is multitenant. There should be a hierarchy account at the top at the very least, but if for some reason you don't qualify for a partner account, they should still be in two separate portals

Matthew Shaver (mshaver@us.ibm.com)
2019-10-14 14:32:54

*Thread Reply:* Being a cloud based solution with a finite set of IPs, we have to limit how often calls our made from our servers to Apple systems. You can raise an RFE to see if there is anything that can be done about your specific scenario, Outlook is a popular app. How often are your VPP tokens being updated that a 2 hour sync window is insufficient? We might be able to open a ticket to work something out, but it’s going to depend on the kind of traffic you’re generating.

Regardless of the sync windows - we can’t actually push older versions of apps, so even if our portal info reflects the previous version of the apps, the devices should receive whatever the current app store version is when it is actually installed

Samsung Android 10 Zero Day Readiness
In preparation for the upcoming Android 10 OS release for Samsung devices, the MaaS360 Android agent v6.82 will be released on November 12, 2019. It is critical that the MaaS360 Android agent v6.82 be installed prior to upgrading the Android OS to Android 10. In addition, Samsung is changing the application ID of their Samsung ‘Contacts’ app. If customers have this application ID is entered in any policy fields this will need to be updated. Details below.

When an iOS app is released and made public in the Apple App Store how soon should we see this new app version in the portal? When should we see this app be available for the users in the MaaS360 App Catalog? (As per info we're using Apple DEP with iOS VPP for our managed iPhones)

Matthew Shaver (mshaver@us.ibm.com)
2020-04-01 21:01:30

*Thread Reply:* We do auto updates once a week (I believe late night Sundays eastern). It will just depend on when the app was released - so if released on a Monday, you'll have to wait about 7 days, but if released on a Friday, only 2. You can manually refresh in the app view, and the app actually delivered will always be the newer version, even if the catalog still displays the old version number

Matthew Shaver (mshaver@us.ibm.com)
2020-04-22 20:36:47

*Thread Reply:* Chrome management got a lot of people hyped, but the realities of it cooled any flames there were.

It requires a paid subscription via Google services, it is a sync with their environment, so users don't actually enroll with MaaS360, they enroll with Google and we sync up the info. Any policies executed via MaaS360 are just a sync back to their environment.

Creating the video was difficult because we couldn't get a VM or similar working to show ll the workflows, but we have some documents on the features.

https://www.ibm.com/support/pages/support-chrome-os

For everything else I refer folks to the goolge documentation: https://support.google.com/chrome/a/answer/1289314?hl=en

ibm.com
Support for Chrome OS
Information about the Chrome OS beta support
Original URL: https://www.ibm.com/support/pages/support-chrome-os
support.google.com
About Chrome device management - Google Chrome Enterprise Help
For administrators who manage Chrome devices for a business or school. As an IT admin for a business or school, you can manage Chromebooks and other Chrome devices, from a cloud-based Admin console.
Original URL: https://support.google.com/chrome/a/answer/1289314?hl=en

If anyone is using Secure Mail against O365, and using the SSO Configuration to achieve modern auth capabilities outlined in this article: https://www.ibm.com/support/knowledgecenter/SS8H2S/com.ibm.mc.doc/pag_source/tasks/modern_auth_clientid.htm .... and is now having auth-loops since Tuesday, Microsoft has made a change to single-tenant Azure apps using a public URL for auth... as in they broke it. Azure logs point to an error: 50194...

That document should be updated to require step 3 to be changed to "Accounts in any organizational directory (Multitenant)"... just went through this with a client, tested a new Azure app, and also by modifying existing Azure app as outlined in the document, by changing to multi-tenant. Both methods worked, and client can continue with new enrollments.

Does anyone have any insight or best practice into ensuring KME to DO enrollments are forced to enroll? Currently, if you set up KME to DO, DO is enabled, MaaS360 application is installed and pinned. User must enter email address and corporate ID, then creds, then all set... the problem here is that if a user reboots their phone at this point, MaaS360 is no longer pinned.

I've tried userless enrollment, which enrolls the device, then made default AFW policy pin (COSU Kiosk) the MaaS360 app, where they then need to log in with creds, then dynamic policy assignment takes over, but this sure feels like a lengthy work-around.

Jordan Philip (jordan.philip@mobilesolutions.net)
2020-08-26 17:51:50

*Thread Reply:* @Matthew Shaver let me know if you have any thoughts on this, or if I'm just missing something simple here.

Matthew Shaver (mshaver@us.ibm.com)
2020-08-26 17:59:21

*Thread Reply:* Upon reboot the app becomes unpinned because we didn't want to inadvertently create a scenario where we essentially brick the device is something is happening in the background that can not be addressed because the app is pinned. So, we made it so that when the device reboots, yes the app is unpinned, but there is a security policy put in place that restricts some of the most basic functionality of the device, like the app store.

Even though there is a policy in place, it's hard coded in to our app, not really enrolled in MaaS360.

In summary - you're not missing anything, it's just the way the platform behaves to ensure that we don't create a scenario where we brick the device.

Matthew Shaver (mshaver@us.ibm.com)
2020-08-26 18:00:37

*Thread Reply:* We did leave the phone functionality intact because there were concerns over restricting this without an explicit admin policy enabled due to emergency call features

Jordan Philip (jordan.philip@mobilesolutions.net)
2020-08-26 18:01:33

*Thread Reply:* I totally get the emergency phone thing, was considering this myself, and thought about doing a default policy with COSU kiosk restricting to phone and MaaS360 app

Matthew Shaver (mshaver@us.ibm.com)
2020-08-26 18:52:20

*Thread Reply:* "Bricking" being a wide term, in some cases this could be desired, but in others not so much - say for example the device requires a critical update to complete enrollment (rare, but not unheard of). In this case it would create a catch-22 where the device would have to be removed from the enrollment program in order to remediate. It's a larger concern for devices that are at the cusp of AE management, but there are a lot of those types of devices still around

has anyone ever seen java memorydump issue with their cloud extender services. I have raised a ticket with support but just wondered if anyone had seen this before. Does Java get updated automatically as part of the modules if Auto update is on?

Norton (norton@us.ibm.com)
2020-09-03 12:53:30

*Thread Reply:* The Gateway module does not auto-upgrade when new versions are available. This is by design as mid-upgrade users are not able to connect, so its setup to allow you to control when it applies. You can launch the Configuration Utility which will notify you if a Gateway update is available and you can choose to run the upgrade then

Justin Butts (justin.butts777@gmail.com)
2020-09-04 17:18:07

Hoping to get clarification on these pieces in the User Settings -> intent of the client is to automatically mark accounts that have been removed from Azure as inactive in MaaS360 and automate the deletion of that record. Azure integration is present, but cannot find documentation that explicitly states that is the functionality of the User Settings

Ray Domingue (raydomingue@gmail.com)
2020-09-08 20:05:16

*Thread Reply:* We have this same setup in our environment. Yes it syncs every 4 hours--both new hires and terms. I.E. when a user is hired, the user profile won't load until after the sync with MaaS360/Azure. If a user is termed, the device(s) that belong to the user are then sent a command to the device to Remove Control from the portal so the user doesn't have access to company resources. To expand on the Termed users bit ... once a user is termed, 48 hours later the Remove Control will be sent to the device. This is done I believe in order to prevent an accidental term in the system. So if Jane Smith was supposed to be termed but they accidental termed John Smith, they have that 48 hours time-frame to fix this before it removes the device from the portal and you'll have to re-enroll the device. I would also keep it at 50 in case there is a glitch of sorts with your Azure client (MS never has any bugs right?). 🙂

Does that help @Justin Butts?

Justin Butts (justin.butts777@gmail.com)

Hi there, does anyone have a best practice for pushing a silent installation of the Onedrive application for Win10 enrolled devices over here? Would it be best to do an MSI or push a Microsoft Store version? I don't see MS Store distribution including automatic/silent install. Any guidance or best practice here would be appreciated

Mark Vonk (mark.vonk@dahvo.com)
2020-11-05 21:22:17

OneDrive (sync agent) is by default installed on Windows 10. You can use MDM to deploy Office (using XML) which includes the OneDrive Desktop client (or you install only the client). You can create the XML to push to Windows 10 here; https://config.office.com/ Info on the XML: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/deployoffice/office-deployment-tool-configuration-options How to push the XML with MaaS360: https://www.ibm.com/support/knowledgecenter/SS8H2S/com.ibm.mc.doc/pag_source/concepts/pag_installing_office_365_suite.htm More general OneDrive deployment: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/onedrive/plan-onedrive-enterprise

docs.microsoft.com
Configuration options for the Office Deployment Tool - Deploy Office
Configuration options for the Office Deployment Tool
Original URL: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/deployoffice/office-deployment-tool-configuration-options
docs.microsoft.com
OneDrive guide for enterprises - OneDrive
This article is a guide for enterprises on using OneDrive. Learn about features, planning, configuration, deployment, and management of OneDrive.
Original URL: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/onedrive/plan-onedrive-enterprise

*Thread Reply:* @Philippe Tétreault @Vlad I can confirm that enroll-on-behalf-of works fine using KME to DO. Just set the email address of the "power user" in the Settings page in MaaS360, make sure it matches a user in your MaaS360 directory, use that email address on page 1 of enrollment, then on next page, enter the associated username and domain, and on the next page you'll get the standard EOB screen, auth the super user, and below, enter the target user of the device.

2020-12-14 17:04:16

*Thread Reply:* Yep! https://www.ibm.com/support/pages/node/6376386 for others

ibm.com
Disabled location tracking on PO devices
In the previous releases, the location permission was auto-granted to the MaaS360 app when Android 11 devices were enrolled in Profile Owner (PO) mode, and end-users could not revoke the location permission from MaaS360 Settings. Effective 10.80 and MaaS360 for Android 7.30+, MaaS360 does not auto-grant location permission during the enrollment and ensures that the permission is only granted when geofencing is enabled.
Original URL: https://www.ibm.com/support/pages/node/6376386

When using wildcards such as %email% in an EAS payload, MaaS360 has always used that user attribute as it was at the time of enrollment, and regardless of how the email address may have changed in AD (or local MaaS360 user directory), there's really no changing what gets delivered in the payload... anyone have a best practice for a customer who just got acquired and changed the email address of every one of their O365 users? One suggestion (from client) is to yank EAS payload and tell the users to just set up the email account using autodiscover... but looking for other options. Another thought was to use , which has worked in the past.

Woody (eric.woodland@trust.tc)
2020-12-16 20:52:45

*Thread Reply:* @Jordan Philip That’s umm.. interesting. So MaaS doesn’t detect the new email address attribute on the source account and push an update to associated devices? So even if you created an new EAS profile, it would still push the former address?

Jordan Philip (jordan.philip@mobilesolutions.net)
2020-12-16 21:03:30

*Thread Reply:* @Woody Correct, you can create a new EAS policy and push that, and the same email address from the device summary page will be pushed in the payload. Selective wipe/revocation doesn't do it either. It seems (and always has) that the device summary page is out of sync with the user directory. This is probably by design, but I'm not sure why yet.

Norton (norton@us.ibm.com)
2020-12-16 21:03:39

*Thread Reply:* Jordan is correct, one option here is adding a custom user attribute, especially if they are tied to an AD setup. You can map that attribute to the new field and then create a new policy that points to that attribute as opposed to %email%

*Thread Reply:* In my experience this is a Samsung specific issue that happens specifically after a restart or shutdown of the device and is related to a setting called strong protection. If you check your will also notice that you can’t locate the device in google find my phone either when the device is locked after a restart or shutdown. Strong protection seems to block a whole load of services.

Robert Schafer (robert.schafer@subsidium-ms.com)
2021-06-01 19:31:24

*Thread Reply:* Hi Philippe, This will be down to device admin deprecation, which specifically includes USESPOLICYLIMIT_PASSWORD which is what the compliance policy most likely uses

More information on this can be found here: https://developers.google.com/android/work/device-admin-deprecation

You need to enroll any android device (android 6 or above recommended) going forward using android enterprise which is the new standard of device management. This is also why it worked when you enrolled the device as profile owner as this is one of the forms of android enterprise.

Here’s some info that is specific to maas360:

https://www.ibm.com/docs/en/maas360?topic=setup-configuring-android-enterprise-maas360

Hope this helps!

Google Developers
Device admin deprecation  |  Android Enterprise  |  Google Developers
Original URL: https://developers.google.com/android/work/device-admin-deprecation
ibm.com
Configuring Android Enterprise with MaaS360
Android Enterprise provides a fast, streamlined method for deploying your corporate-owned Android devices.
Original URL: https://www.ibm.com/docs/en/maas360?topic=setup-configuring-android-enterprise-maas360

Justin Butts (justin.butts777@gmail.com)
2022-03-25 14:38:53

Do MaaS360 DEP enrollments require a user to launch the MaaS360 agent to tie the DEP registration to the device at all post setup? I am struggling to remember if this is required in MaaS360

Robert Schafer (robert.schafer@subsidium-ms.com)
2022-03-25 15:50:15

*Thread Reply:* DEP comes into play as soon as the device hits apple services for the first time, at which point it retrieves its enrollment profile based on the mdm server it's assigned too, then depending on your DEP profile setup in maas it will either require the user to authenticate or not. If you don't require authentication then you MUST assign a user manually to the device after the device enrolls and appears in the maas console. If you don't assign a user and you don't have ‘deploy apps and configurations to devices without authentication' enabled in settings nothing will apply.

👍 Justin Butts
Will Davis (wmdavis@us.ibm.com)
2022-03-31 22:20:20

*Thread Reply:* The MaaS app does not have to be launched to enroll into DEP, but it is required for things like Location, data usage management, jail broken detection, etc

👍 Woody
